 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Telemetry Signal Analysis & DSP Filtering\n",
    "\n",
    "**Objective:** Process high-frequency synthetic telemetry from the SafeACS 3-axis simulation to identify structurally threatening resonant frequencies (simulated as EMI or mechanical vibration) and apply a digital low-pass filter to clean the signal before it reaches the AI heuristic engine.\n",
    "\n",
    "*Demonstrates Core Electrical Engineering competencies (EDU_CSULA_03, CSULA EE 332 Systems Analysis).*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from scipy.fft import fft, fftfreq\n",
    "from scipy.signal import butter, lfilter, freqz\n",
    "\n",
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "# 1. Generate Synthetic Telemetry (Mirroring ACS Simulator)\n",
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "fs = 100.0       # Sample rate (Hz)\n",
    "T = 10.0         # Duration (Seconds)\n",
    "n = int(T * fs)  # Total samples\n",
    "t = np.linspace(0, T, n, endpoint=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Base nominal signal (Reaction Wheel RPM gradually increasing)\n",
    "base_rpm = 2000.0 + (50 * t)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Inject EMI Noise (60Hz) and a resonant mechanical vibration (15Hz)\n",
    "noise_60hz = 150 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * 60 * t)\n",
    "resonance_15hz = 300 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * 15 * t)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Combined noisy telemetry signal\n",
    "raw_sensor_data = base_rpm + noise_60hz + resonance_15hz + np.random.normal(0, 20, n)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "plt.plot(t, raw_sensor_data, label='Raw Telemetry', color='#e74c3c', alpha=0.8)\n",
    "plt.title('Time Domain: Noisy ACS Wheel RPM (Raw Sensor Output)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Time [sec]')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('RPM')\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Frequency Domain Analysis (Fast Fourier Transform)\n",
    "To isolate the specific noise profiles corrupting the Pydantic guardrails, we transition the signal from the time-domain into the frequency-domain using an FFT."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "# 2. Fast Fourier Transform (FFT)\n",
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "yf = fft(raw_sensor_data)\n",
    "xf = fftfreq(n, 1 / fs)[:n//2]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "plt.plot(xf, 2.0/n * np.abs(yf[0:n//2]), color='#9b59b6')\n",
    "plt.title('Frequency Domain: Fast Fourier Transform (FFT)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Frequency [Hz]')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Amplitude')\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Annotate the known noise spikes\n",
    "plt.axvline(15, color='orange', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5, label='Mechanial Resonance (15Hz)')\n",
    "plt.axvline(60, color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5, label='EMI Interference (60Hz)')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Designing the Digital Filter (Butterworth Low-Pass)\n",
    "With the noise isolated at 15Hz and 60Hz, we design an Infinite Impulse Response (IIR) Butterworth low-pass filter with a cutoff frequency of 5Hz. This allows the core attitude control kinematics (which change relatively slowly) to pass through, while aggressively attenuating the resonant vibrations and EMI before they trigger a false positive in the AI guardrail layer."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "# 3. Butterworth Low-Pass Filter Implementation\n",
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "def butter_lowpass(cutoff, fs, order=5):\n",
    "    nyq = 0.5 * fs\n",
    "    normal_cutoff = cutoff / nyq\n",
    "    b, a = butter(order, normal_cutoff, btype='low', analog=False)\n",
    "    return b, a\n",
    "\n",
    "def butter_lowpass_filter(data, cutoff, fs, order=5):\n",
    "    b, a = butter_lowpass(cutoff, fs, order=order)\n",
    "    y = lfilter(b, a, data)\n",
    "    return y\n",
    "\n",
    "# Filter requirements.\n",
    "cutoff = 5.0  # desired cutoff frequency of the filter, Hz\n",
    "order = 6\n",
    "\n",
    "filtered_data = butter_lowpass_filter(raw_sensor_data, cutoff, fs, order)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))\n",
    "plt.plot(t, raw_sensor_data, 'lightgray', label='Raw Noisy Telemetry')\n",
    "plt.plot(t, filtered_data, '#2ecc71', linewidth=2.5, label='Filtered Signal (Sent to Edge Guardrails)')\n",
    "plt.plot(t, base_rpm, 'k--', label='True Physical State', alpha=0.7)\n",
    "plt.title('Time Domain: Filtered vs Raw Telemetry')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Time [sec]')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('RPM')\n",
    "plt.legend(loc='upper left')\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  }
 ],
